Graphing

Introduction

As is so often the case, there are multiple packages for doing graphs in R. There is base functionality, which hardly anyone seems to use, and then two main contenders: ggplot2 and lattice. Here’s an introduction to ggplot2.

library(ggplot2)

mycars <- mtcars
mycars$car <- rownames(mycars)
rownames(mycars) <- NULL

There are three components to any ggplot call:

  • data
  • “aesthetic mappings” map data to visual properties
  • geometric objects (points, lines etc)

Basic examples

Plot points mpg (x-axis) vs wt (y-axis)

ggplot(data = mycars, aes(x = mpg, y = wt)) +
  geom_point()

Add a lowess smoother:

ggplot(mycars, aes(x = mpg, y = wt)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_smooth()

Or labels:

ggplot(mycars, aes(x = mpg, y = wt)) +
    geom_point()  +
    geom_text(aes(label = car))

(Use geom_text_repel from the ggrepel package to improve the labelling)

Provide options to geom functions:

ggplot(mycars, aes(x = mpg, y = wt)) + 
        geom_point(color="royalblue", size = 2)  +
        geom_smooth(method=lm, se = FALSE, color="grey")

Set aesthetic mappings for individual geoms, e.g. color:

ggplot(mycars,  aes(x = mpg, y = wt)) + 
        geom_point(aes(color=qsec)) + 
        geom_smooth(method=lm, se = FALSE, color="red")

.. or size:

ggplot(mycars,  aes(x = mpg, y = wt)) + 
        geom_point(aes(size=qsec)) + 
        geom_smooth(method=lm, se = FALSE, color="red")

.. or shape (having turned “am”" into a factor):

ggplot(mycars,  aes(x = mpg, y = wt)) + 
        geom_point(aes(shape=factor(am)),size=3) + 
        geom_smooth(method=lm, se = FALSE, color="red")

See the difference to setting the aesthetic mapping on the whole plot:

ggplot(mycars,  aes(x = mpg, y = wt, shape=factor(am))) + 
        geom_point(size=3) + 
        geom_smooth(method=lm, se = FALSE, color="red")

Set title and axis labels:

ggplot(mycars,  aes(x = mpg, y = wt)) +
         geom_point()  +
         geom_smooth(method=lm, se = FALSE, color="red") +
         xlab("Fuel Economy") + 
         ylab("Weight") + 
         ggtitle("Cars")

Use the geom_histogram() function to create a histogram

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = price)) + 
         geom_histogram()

Set the bin width:

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = price)) + 
         geom_histogram(binwidth = 10)

Use geom_bar() to create a bar chart

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = clarity)) +
  geom_bar()

.. or by group:

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = clarity)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill = cut))

Hide the legend:

ggplot(diamonds, aes(x = clarity)) +
  geom_bar(aes(fill = clarity)) + 
  theme(legend.position = "none")

Density

ggplot(diamonds, aes(price)) + 
  geom_histogram(aes(y = ..density..), binwidth = 500)

Density estimate:

ggplot(diamonds, aes(price)) + 
  geom_density(aes(fill = cut))

Change the legend label:

ggplot(diamonds, aes(price)) + 
  geom_density(aes(fill = cut)) + 
  labs(fill = "Cut quality")

Change the theme:

ggplot(diamonds, aes(price)) + 
  geom_density(aes(fill = cut)) + 
  labs(fill = "Cut quality") + 
  theme_bw()

ggplot2 and ‘tidy’ data

Make sure you get data into a ‘tidy’ (long) form before using ggplot2. For example:

library(dplyr)
library(tidyr)
library(readr)

unemployment <- read_csv("http://markwestcott34.github.io/economics/teaching/ss2015/R/datasets/uk_unemployment.csv")

head(unemployment)
## Source: local data frame [6 x 3]
## 
##    Year   Men Women
##   (int) (dbl) (dbl)
## 1  2000   5.9   4.9
## 2  2001   5.6   4.4
## 3  2002   5.8   4.5
## 4  2003   5.6   4.4
## 5  2004   5.1   4.3
## 6  2005   5.3   4.4
unemployment_tidy <-
    gather(unemployment, key = Gender, value = "unemployment_rate", Men:Women)

head(unemployment_tidy %>% arrange(Year))
## Source: local data frame [6 x 3]
## 
##    Year Gender unemployment_rate
##   (int) (fctr)             (dbl)
## 1  2000    Men               5.9
## 2  2000  Women               4.9
## 3  2001    Men               5.6
## 4  2001  Women               4.4
## 5  2002    Men               5.8
## 6  2002  Women               4.5
ggplot(data = unemployment_tidy, aes(x = Year, y = unemployment_rate)) +
  geom_point()

ggplot(data = unemployment_tidy, aes(x = Year, y = unemployment_rate)) +
  geom_line()

ggplot(data = unemployment_tidy, aes(x = Year, y = unemployment_rate, color=Gender)) +
  geom_line()

Scales

In order to control axis, size, colour, position, we use scales

df <- data.frame(x = (1:7) * 1000, y = sin(sqrt(1:7)), z = c("a","b","b","c","d","e","e"))
p <- ggplot(df, aes(x = x, y = y, colour = factor(z))) + 
  geom_point(size = 10)

p

  p + scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(2000, 4000,6000))

  p + scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(2000, 4000,6000), labels = c("2k","4k","6k"))

  p + scale_x_continuous(breaks = c(2000, 4000,6000)) +
      scale_y_continuous(labels = scales::percent)

  p + scale_y_continuous(limits = c(0,1.5))

  p + scale_colour_grey()

  p + scale_colour_brewer(palette = "Pastel1") #See http://a2.typepad.com/6a0105360ba1c6970c01b7c7187af2970b-pi for available palettes

  p + scale_color_manual("Letter", values = c("a" = "red", b = "orange", c = "yellow", d = "pink", e = "green"))

Graph exercise

Recreate this graph from the Economist:

using the data at http://www.markw.de/economics/teaching/ss2016/R/other/EconomistData.csv

Try the following steps:

  • Create a scatter plot
  • Color points by region
  • Add a quadratic smoothing line (hint: look at the ‘formula’ argument in the help for stat_smooth)
  • Add labels (but only to some countries!)
  • Set x and y axis titles

Have a look at the ggrepel package to improve the labelling of elements.

Wrap up

  • basic operations

  • lists
  • *apply functions
  • loading Stata/CSV data into R

  • regressions (OLS, probit, logit, robust SEs, bootstrapped SEs)
  • dplyr for efficient data manipulation
  • tidyr for reshaping and tidying data
  • LaTeX/R integration
  • graphs with ggplot2
